INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '6a3f7563-08e6-4947-a780-cd3c37076fb2',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$styled_components Layout Primitives — Flexbox vs Grid and When to Reach for Each$escape$,
  $escape$Flexbox and Grid solve different problems. In styled_components, model each as a reusable primitive rather than scattering layout logic across components.

Use a `Flex` primitive when content drives layout — nav bars, button groups, card rows where items expand or shrink. `display: flex` with `gap`, `align-items`, and `justify-content` props covers 90% of one-dimensional cases. Accept props directly via tagged template interpolations so callers control axis without overriding class names.

Use a `Grid` primitive for two-dimensional structure — dashboard shells, article grids, form layouts where rows and columns must align across cells. `grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(...))` inside styled-components gives you responsive columns without a single media query import.

Avoid mixing both on the same element — it signals unclear ownership of layout responsibility. Compose them: a `Grid` shell defines macro structure; `Flex` children handle micro-alignment within each cell.

Keep layout primitives prop-driven and style-only. They should own no semantic HTML — let callers pass `as` to swap the underlying element without touching layout logic.$escape$,
  $escape$import styled from 'styled-components';

interface FlexProps {
  direction?: 'row' | 'column';
  gap?: string;
  align?: string;
  justify?: string;
}

export const Flex = styled.div<FlexProps>`
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: ${p => p.direction ?? 'row'};
  gap: ${p => p.gap ?? '0'};
  align-items: ${p => p.align ?? 'stretch'};
  justify-content: ${p => p.justify ?? 'flex-start'};
`;

interface GridProps {
  columns?: string;
  gap?: string;
}

export const Grid = styled.div<GridProps>`
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: ${p => p.columns ?? 'repeat(auto-fill, minmax(240px, 1fr))'};
  gap: ${p => p.gap ?? '1rem'};
`;

// Usage
// <Grid columns="repeat(3, 1fr)" gap="2rem">
//   <Flex direction="column" gap="0.5rem" as="article">...</Flex>
// </Grid>$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
