INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '69b0e4b5-7399-4405-877f-bb2cadc13cd3',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$styled_components — Winning Specificity Wars Without !important$escape$,
  $escape$styled_components generates a unique className per component, but that alone doesn't prevent specificity wars — it relocates them. The real battleground is injection order: when you extend with `styled(Base)`, overrides inject after the base and win by source order. That's fine for your own components. The problem surfaces with third-party sc components or `createGlobalStyle` blocks — both emit single-class selectors, so whichever injects last wins, and that order flips unpredictably between SSR and CSR hydration.

The `&&` doubling pattern solves this without `!important`. It compiles to `.sc-abc.sc-abc`, bumping specificity to `[0,2,0]` and cleanly beating any single-class override.

Utility-first CSS avoids the problem entirely by keeping all rules at `[0,1,0]` — one atomic class per property, no nesting, no cascade conflicts. In styled_components, approximate this discipline: define atomic `css` blocks via the `css` helper, compose them through template literal interpolation, and never nest selectors. Pair with `ThemeProvider` tokens to keep your design system centralized while keeping specificity flat. The result: predictable override behavior without an arms race.$escape$,
  $escape$import styled, { css } from 'styled-components';

const Base = styled.div`background: white; border-radius: 8px;`;

// && compiles to [0,2,0] — beats any single-class third-party override
const Themed = styled(Base)`
  && {
    background: ${({ theme }) => theme.colors.surface};
  }
`;

// Atomic-style block: one concern, flat specificity, composable
const surfacePad = css`padding: ${({ theme }) => theme.space[4]};`;

const Card = styled(Themed)`${surfacePad}`;$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
