INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '141e09e1-ba4a-445d-b9ad-8ca86b3ee888',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$styled_components — Runtime Theming with CSS Custom Properties$escape$,
  $escape$styled_components' ThemeProvider injects theme tokens as JavaScript values at render time — but CSS Custom Properties let you push those tokens into the DOM, enabling instant theme switches without re-rendering every styled component.

Instead of interpolating `${({ theme }) => theme.colors.primary}` on every component, define your theme as CSS variables in a single `createGlobalStyle` block. styled_components still owns the source of truth via ThemeProvider, but you bridge it to the cascade with a global style that maps JS tokens to `--var` names.

Scoping works naturally: drop a second `createGlobalStyle` (or a styled `div`) with overriding `--var` values to create a dark panel, a high-contrast widget, or a brand-specific zone — all without prop drilling or nested ThemeProviders.

JavaScript interop stays clean: read `getComputedStyle(el).getPropertyValue('--color-primary')` for runtime reads, or call `el.style.setProperty` for imperative overrides (useful for animation or user-driven palette pickers). The styled component never needs to know — it just consumes the variable.$escape$,
  $escape$import { createGlobalStyle, ThemeProvider, styled } from 'styled-components';

const theme = { colors: { primary: '#6200ea', surface: '#ffffff' } };

const CSSTokens = createGlobalStyle<{ theme: typeof theme }>`
  :root {
    --color-primary: ${({ theme }) => theme.colors.primary};
    --color-surface: ${({ theme }) => theme.colors.surface};
  }
`;

const Card = styled.div`
  background: var(--color-surface);
  border-left: 4px solid var(--color-primary);
`;

// Dark zone — no extra ThemeProvider needed
const DarkCard = styled(Card)`
  --color-surface: #1a1a2e;
  --color-primary: #bb86fc;
`;$escape$,
