INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'fbbdc58e-9585-4fb3-aa25-618541fd9b34',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$styled-components Performance — Critical CSS, Layout Thrash, and the will-change Trap$escape$,
  $escape$styled-components injects component styles lazily into a runtime <style> tag — only rendered components contribute to the CSS payload. On the server, pair ServerStyleSheet with collectStyles() to extract and inline critical CSS before the first byte hits the client, eliminating FOUC without a separate extraction build step.

Layout thrash sneaks in when dynamic interpolations depend on DOM geometry. If you're passing getBoundingClientRect() values as transient props ($width, $height) to a styled-component, those reads inside a React render force synchronous reflows. Batch all DOM reads in a useLayoutEffect, cache the values in state, then pass them as props on the next paint.

will-change: transform in a styled-component feels free — it isn't. Each promoted layer consumes GPU memory and triggers a repaint at mount and unmount. Gate it with a transient prop ($isAnimating) and a css interpolation, applying it only during the active animation window. Never set will-change inside createGlobalStyle targeting a broad selector — you'll silently promote hundreds of elements and tank memory on low-end devices.$escape$,
  $escape$import styled, { css } from 'styled-components';

// Bad: permanent will-change promoted on every mounted instance
const Card = styled.div`
  will-change: transform;
  transition: transform 0.2s ease;
`;

// Good: gate via transient prop — promote only during animation
const AnimatedCard = styled.div<{ $isAnimating: boolean }>`
  transition: transform 0.2s ease;
  ${({ $isAnimating }) =>
    $isAnimating &&
    css`
      will-change: transform;
    `}
`;$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
