INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '029cd455-ec59-4129-9a31-5cfcec2f5e77',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$styled_components — Linting and Formatting CSS-in-JS with Stylelint, Prettier, and PostCSS$escape$,
  $escape$styled_components interpolates CSS inside tagged template literals, which means standard CSS linters skip over it entirely. Fix this with `stylelint-config-styled-components` paired with `@stylelint/postcss-css-in-js` — together they parse the CSS out of your `styled.div\`...\`` blocks and run your full Stylelint ruleset against it.

In your `.stylelintrc`, extend `stylelint-config-styled-components` and set `customSyntax: '@stylelint/postcss-css-in-js'`. This lets rules like `color-no-invalid-hex` and `shorthand-property-no-redundant-values` catch mistakes inside template literals before they ship.

For Prettier, `prettier-plugin-styled-components` (now bundled into Prettier 3's `prettier-plugin-css-in-js`) reformats the CSS inside your tagged templates — aligning properties, normalizing quotes, and collapsing redundant declarations — without touching the surrounding JS.

For PostCSS transforms (autoprefixer, `postcss-logical`), use `babel-plugin-styled-components` with its `displayName` and `pure` flags in development, and configure a `postcss.config.js` — styled_components will pipe interpolated CSS through PostCSS during the Babel transform step, so vendor prefixes land in the generated class names automatically.$escape$,
  $escape$// .stylelintrc.json
{
  "customSyntax": "@stylelint/postcss-css-in-js",
  "extends": ["stylelint-config-standard", "stylelint-config-styled-components"],
  "rules": {
    "color-no-invalid-hex": true,
    "shorthand-property-no-redundant-values": true
  }
}

// postcss.config.js
module.exports = {
  plugins: [
    require('autoprefixer'),
    require('postcss-logical')
  ]
};$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
